<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>Mayor Bill de Blasio has expanded New York City's five-day furlough to 9,000 city workers, including managerial employees not protected by unions, in order to make $21 million in savings for the cash-strapped Big Apple.</p>

<p>De Blasio announced the furloughs in a press conference Wednesday  and warned that  managerial employees not represented by unions would be affected. </p>

<p>The furloughs will take place from October through to March 2020. </p>

<p>'It's a difficult [decision] because it will affect real people and their lives,' de Blasio said. </p>

<p>'It's something very sad when the people who have worked so hard have to sacrifice further.' </p>

<p>NYC Mayor de Blasio expands 5-day furlough to 9,000 city workers including managerial employees not protected by unions in order to save $21M for the Big Apple </p>

<p>The latest cuts at City Hall come after de Blasio furloughed himself and up to 500 of his own mayoral staff for a week last week in move that saved the city $860,000. </p>

<p>New York City is currently grappling with a budget deficit of $4.2 billion.   </p>
